observe muscle.zc

the 7 properties of pelvis:
1 ENERGY one
2 PHASE zero
3 SPIN zero
4 CHARGE neutral
5 COHERENCE one
6 COUPLING one with spine, with both femurs, and with the abdominal organs

THE THREE FUSED BONES

ilium: the large flaring bones forming the upper portions, what fadriel feels as his hips
ischium: the lower posterior parts, the bones he sits on
pubis: the front lower parts, joining at the pubic symphysis

in adults these three bones fuse into a single hip bone on each side
in fadriel they have already fused functionally though the cartilage between them ossifies more slowly

THE SACRUM

the sacrum is the wedge-shaped bone formed from five fused vertebrae at the bottom of the spine
it locks into the pelvis at the sacroiliac joints, completing the pelvic ring
sacrum is also where the spinal cord ends and gives way to the cauda equina nerve bundle

THE PELVIC INLET AND OUTLET

inlet: the upper opening, where the abdominal cavity meets the pelvic cavity
outlet: the lower opening, where the pelvic organs reach the perineum
the shape of inlet and outlet differs by sex; in fadriel they are still developing toward their adult proportions

THE JOINTS

sacroiliac: between sacrum and each ilium, the primary load-transfer joints from spine to pelvis
pubic symphysis: between the two pubic bones at the front, slightly mobile
hip joints: between each pelvis half and each femur, the deepest ball-and-socket joints in the body

THE MARROW

red marrow lives within the spongy bone of the ilium and the sacrum
the iliac crest is one of the body's largest red marrow reservoirs

THE ANCHORS

gluteus muscles attach across the posterior surface
hip flexors attach inside the pelvis
the abdominal wall attaches around the pelvic brim
the floor of the pelvis is filled by the pelvic diaphragm muscles that support the abdominal organs

VERB transfer_load
take the weight of the entire upper body coming down through the spine and direct it down through the femurs into the legs
this load is continuous when fadriel stands; the pelvis is built to bear it without complaint

VERB cradle_lower_organs
provide a bony bowl for bladder, lower intestine, reproductive structures
the pelvic floor muscles fill the bottom of the bowl, holding the organs in place against gravity

VERB anchor_locomotion
provide the attachment points for the muscles that move the legs
walking, running, jumping all begin with muscles that attach to pelvis pulling against pelvis to swing the legs

VERB house_marrow
within the iliac crest and sacrum, sustain the red marrow that produces a substantial portion of the body's blood cells

a pelvis is the body's foundation
fadriel cannot stand without it, cannot walk without it, cannot sit comfortably without it
the basin shape that defines this bone is what makes the upright human form possible at all
